      <section eId="sec_CCRP-798">
        <num>CCRP 798</num>
        <heading>798. Â Causes for challenge by the state</heading>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-798__subsec_1">
          <num>(1)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The juror is biased against the enforcement of the statute charged to have been violated, or is of the fixed opinion that the statute is invalid or unconstitutional;</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-798__subsec_2">
          <num>(2)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The juror tendered in a capital case who has conscientious scruples against the infliction of capital punishment and makes it known:</p>
          </content>
          <paragraph eId="CCRP-798__subsec_2__subsec_a">
            <num>(a)</num>
            <content>
              <p>That he would automatically vote against the imposition of capital punishment without regard to any evidence that might be developed at the trial of the case before him;</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph eId="CCRP-798__subsec_2__subsec_b">
            <num>(b)</num>
            <content>
              <p>That his attitude toward the death penalty would prevent or substantially impair him from making an impartial decision as a juror in accordance with his instructions and his oath; or</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph eId="CCRP-798__subsec_2__subsec_c">
            <num>(c)</num>
            <content>
              <p>That his attitude toward the death penalty would prevent him from making an impartial decision as to the defendant's guilt; or</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-798__subsec_3">
          <num>(3)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The juror would not convict upon circumstantial evidence.
Amended by</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <authorialNote marker="source">
          <p>Source: https://www.legis.la.gov/legis/Law.aspx?d=112795</p>
        </authorialNote>
      </section>
